With the restrictions shown on the app with regard to bank balances, that check to see if you have money in your account or not, will automatically deny your request for a $20 float. The irony is that if I HAD money in my bank account, the necessity to use Float Me wouldn‚Äôt exist. As a frequent user, Float Me needs to update their rules in order to help those of us who do not currently have money in their account for a couple of days until payday. We are struggling out here and that $20 could and does keep us from struggling or literally being hungry. My opinion? A bank balance containing cash makes using Float Me rather redundant. This rule should be rethought. This app is useless if a zero balance is the determining factor Thanks for taking the time to read my opinion.

developerResponse: {'id': 19886682, 'body': "Thanks NeslyLeon, we appreciate your detailed review! We understand that there are other platforms that offer larger amounts- we intentionally do not for a few reasons. We actually tried doing to up to $200 back in 2018 when we were testing; we found that most of our members actually only needed $15- $25 to prevent an overdraft- not hundreds of dollars. By offering smaller amounts, we're able to do three key things: 1) Help our members avoid overborrowing. Pew Charitable Trust, the Federal Reserve, and our own research has shown that most platforms encourage their members to overborrow, causing them to become trapped in a debt cycle. We don't believe in doing that and focus on making sure our members can afford to repay their Floats without disrupting their lives. 2) It lets us keep our costs low. We are able to afford to offer free standard floats and have a very low monthly membership fee because there is a LOT less risk when you only float $20 - $30 to a new member vs. $200; a certain number of people unfortunately take advantage and try not to pay us back- the smaller amount helps us avoid having our responsible members be harmed by this. 3) We're able to help more people. If we have $1000 to offer floats, we can only help 5 people if we offer $200 floats. By offering a starting amount of $20 we can help 50 of our members; this is extra important during these very challenging times.\n\nI hope that this helps answer your question and that one day you'll see us as an affordable and thoughtful 5-star service as we continue to release new features and tools for all our members :)", 'modified': '2020-12-21T03:03:04Z'}

review: Good to start with but the amounts need to be higher at-least $100 would be great like the apps earning and Dave. The pay back should be longer as well to give people time.
developerResponse: {'id': 20017292, 'body': "Hi David41390, thank you for sharing your ideas! We intentionally do not offer larger floats for a few reasons. First, we found during our research and interviews with our members that the average expense causing an overdraft was $15 - $25;to help our members most needed  just around that amount. Second, we are committed to helping our members prevent overborrowing and only take out what they can afford to repay without undue hardship and based our limits on research by Pew Charitable Trusts and the Federal Reserve. Third, lower limits let us help more people with the same amount of money. If we have $2000 to extend floats, we can only help 20 members if we set starting limits at $100. Instead, we're able to help 100 members with $20 starting limits. Regarding repayment, we follow the rules set by Federal CFPB Early Wage Access regulations; we also do not charge late fees if a member does not have funds to repay on the due date. I hope that this helps you understand better!", 'modified': '2020-12-27T19:28:40Z'}

review: I downloaded this when I was short handed one week. It was nice because the approval process was simple, and I got $10 sent to me for gas, and then $20 later when I needed it again. HOWEVER, I have tried over and over again without fail for WEEKS to login to my account and it claims that ‚ÄúPlaid‚Äù, whom they use to link your bank account, will not allow me to re-link my account. I have changed my bank password and logged into my bank, via their website, no problem at all, but every time I try to login to this app, it will not allow me. You cannot find contact information for them anywhere online. I did finally discover a place I could email them and I emailed them well wishing the 30 day ‚Äútrial period‚Äù that I dislike the app function and wish to cancel my account. Never heard a flipping word back from the whatsoever and now they‚Äôve charged me the $1.99 monthly fee, which is unethical, as I specifically requested to cancel the account before the trial period ever ended.  And, as an added surprise, that also makes zero sense, I opened the account in November 10-11, which means the charge should‚Äôve come somewhere around December 10th, yet it charged on the 29th of December, giving me the impression for the past couple of weeks that it was successfully cancelled, despite their failure to respond to my request, then BAM, charged my account. Can an admin please respond to this and refund the $1.99 charge as well as CANCEL THE ACCOUNT. Very unprofessional this unresponsive nature. Seems a lot of people have similar issues.

review:
Hi I test apps and leave reviews for consumers for free cause the world is the world, this review is honest and mentions all personal experiences of using this app nothing is fabricated nor over exaggerated. Im not affiliated with any company.

Key Experience: this app will overdraft your account it doesn't pay its self back properly, days will pass before float attempts to take back borrowed funds this app is not practical 

Summary of app/ experience 

This app will allow you to withdraw money within your pay period for 1.99 a month. IMMEDIATE withdrawal comes with a $4 fee, FREE withdrawal takes 2-3 business days to reach your account. ‚ÄúOnly‚Äù $10 or $20 are allowed to be withdrawn for a single period. you will be given an option to increase but that option will remain unavailable at the discretion of the developers. They tell you how your able to increase the balance but after tinkering with the different ways to increase I didn't receive one. After contacting the developers and asking for an increase in my balance I was ignored which seems to be the story of many here in the comments ‚Äú want more money, TO BAD pay me! There are requirements to withdraw funds early, such as having a balance above $0.00 and a positive payment history with float, they also require at least 3 consecutive deposits of no less than $200.00 and you cant have any large atm withdrawals after or prior to your payday. So if your in need for immediate financial help please go to recommendations or keep looking.

Wrap- up / recommendations 

These requirements seem normal for a company looking to lend money to strangers ;however, this app doesn't seem to fully fulfill its end of the deal. If your in need of an advancement in your paycheck with minimum hurdles my recommendation would be Earnin they
have a large burrow amount with little to no hassle in getting the funds they have similar requirements and they will charge you on the due date, no need to worry about random unforeseen overdrafts. Float just seems to operate completely autonomously with little human interactions in my opinion. developers are not fast with responding and the interface seems is to simple for a paycheck advancement app. Since installing the app theres been one updated but nothing but the app logo changed. I also get a sketchy vibe because the app states its a financial app but the resources they provide are mediocre everyday articles and opinions from unreliable sources, not to mention they don‚Äôt automatically pull what you borrow like they state and blame you for the mis hap . Float may just be a developer piggy banks
 -2stars
